# Focus-Fork Swift Patterns

## `FocusProduct.isEnabled` usage

We do not need to preserve the stock Telegram experience. Modifying code directly is fine — `FocusProduct.isEnabled` guards are optional and only useful for greppability, not as a requirement. Feel free to change or remove stock behavior unconditionally when it conflicts with the focus fork.

## Section headers in the chat list

Section headers are injected into the entry stream **after sorting** in the `mapToQueue` block of `ChatListController.swift`, not in the data layer. The `UIChatListEntry.sectionHeader(String)` case exists only for this purpose.

## Digest banner

The digest banner is a `UIDigestBannerAction` (conforming to `UIChatListTextAction`). It is inserted as a `.custom(action)` entry. Channels are filtered from the main list (`prepareEntries` → `includeChatListEntry`) and surfaced only via this banner.

## Media placeholders

Replace inline media (photos, stickers, GIFs, video, albums) with `ChatFocusMediaPlaceholderItem` rows. Use `focusPlaceholderLabel(for:)` / `focusGroupedPlaceholderTitle(for:)` helpers in `ChatRowItem.swift` to generate the label string.

## Theme

Never call `updateThemeInteractivetly` or `telegramUpdateTheme` with a dark palette — `Appearance.swift` normalises to light automatically. Do not add new auto-night or system-appearance observers.

## Compose area

Placeholder text for the generic message input in focus mode is `"Write a reply…"` (set in `ChatInputView.textPlaceholder`). Emoji/keyboard/gift buttons are already hidden via `FocusProduct.isEnabled` in `ChatInputActionsView`.
